               <p>EDWARD MORRIS. I am foreman to Mr. Robert Lambert; he is a <rs id="t18320517-265-viclabel1515" type="occupation">coach-proprietor</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320517-265-victim1928 t18320517-265-viclabel1515"></join>, and lives at <placeName id="t18320517-265-crimeloc1516">Blackwall</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320517-265-crimeloc1516" type="placeName" value="Blackwall"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320517-265-crimeloc1516" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320517-265-off1513 t18320517-265-crimeloc1516"></join>. On the 14th of May I missed a bridle bit, which I had seen safe the afternoon before - I accused the prisoner of taking it; the officer produced it to me.</p>
               <p>WILLIAM DICKENSON (Police-constable H 11.) I produce this bit, which I got from Mr. Beacham.</p>
               <p>LEWIS BEACHAM. I live with my father, who keeps a sadler's shop in Whitechapel-road. The prisoner came on the 15th, and offered this bit for sale for 1s. 3d. - my father asked if it was his own; he said it was, and he offered him 1s. for it, which he took.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>The prisoner received a good character, and his master engaged to take him again.</p>
